WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Teacher: Hello class. Today I'm going to explain the water cycle. Please listen carefully and take notes.

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:35.000
Teacher: The water cycle is the continuous movement of water on, above, and below the surface of the Earth.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:01:00.000
Teacher: There are four main stages: evaporation, condensation, precipitation, and collection. Let me explain each one.

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:30.000
Teacher: First, evaporation. This is when the sun heats up water in rivers, lakes, and oceans and turns it into water vapor that rises into the air.

00:01:30.500 --> 00:02:00.000
Teacher: The vapor rises higher and gets cooler. When it cools enough, it condenses into tiny water droplets that form clouds. This is condensation.

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:20.000
Teacher: Any questions so far?

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:25.000
Student 1: Why do clouds form at different heights?

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:45.000
Teacher: Good question. It depends on the temperature and humidity at different altitudes. Higher clouds form in colder conditions.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:03:15.000
Teacher: Now, when the clouds get heavy with water droplets, the water falls back to Earth as precipitation - rain, snow, sleet, or hail.

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:45.000
Teacher: Finally, collection. The water that falls collects in oceans, rivers, lakes, and groundwater. And then the cycle starts again.

00:03:45.500 --> 00:04:00.000
Teacher: I want everyone to copy this diagram into your notebooks. It shows all four stages clearly.

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:30.000
[Students copying]

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:50.000
Teacher: Tomorrow we'll do an experiment to see evaporation and condensation in action.

00:04:50.500 --> 00:05:00.000
Teacher: Please read pages 45 to 48 in your textbook for homework. Class dismissed. 